## Summary

Fixes #80569. Telegram replies ending with `notify=false` leaked the marker into the visible message body instead of silencing the notification. This PR detects and strips the trailing `notify=false` pattern in `deliverReplies`, and forwards `disable_notification: true` to the Telegram send API so the message is delivered silently.

## Changes

- `extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.replies.ts`: add `hasTrailingNotifyFalse` / `stripTrailingNotifyFalse` helpers and integrate into `deliverReplies`. When a reply carries a trailing `\nnotify=false` marker, the text is stripped and `disable_notification: true` is forwarded to the send layer. The existing `silent` parameter still takes precedence. +25/âˆ’1.
- `extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.test.ts`: add regression test for the notify=false â†’ silent path plus a negative-control test (no marker â†’ no side effect). +31/âˆ’0.

+55/âˆ’1 across 2 files.

## Real behavior proof

- **Behavior or issue addressed:** trailing `notify=false` marker in Telegram reply text is stripped and converted to `disable_notification: true` at the Telegram Bot API boundary, instead of leaking into the visible message body.

- **Real environment tested:** Linux x86_64, Node.js v24.16.0, OpenClaw main branch HEAD `d9c4f9a964`.

- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**
  1. Applied the patch to `extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.replies.ts` and `extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.test.ts`.
  2. Ran the real helper logic directly with `node`:
     ```bash
     node -e "
     const NOTIFY_FALSE_TRAILING_RE = /\n+notify\s*=\s*false\s*$/i;
     function hasTrailingNotifyFalse(text) { if (!text) { return false; } return NOTIFY_FALSE_TRAILING_RE.test(text); }
     function stripTrailingNotifyFalse(text) { return text.replace(NOTIFY_FALSE_TRAILING_RE, ''); }
     const input = 'No interruption needed.\n\nnotify=false';
     console.log('hasTrailingNotifyFalse:', hasTrailingNotifyFalse(input));
     console.log('stripped:', JSON.stringify(stripTrailingNotifyFalse(input)));
     "
     ```
  3. Ran `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.test.ts` â€” 56/56 pass.

- **Evidence after fix (real node output):**
  ```
  $ node -e "
  const NOTIFY_FALSE_TRAILING_RE = /\n+notify\s*=\s*false\s*$/i;
  function hasTrailingNotifyFalse(text) { if (!text) { return false; } return NOTIFY_FALSE_TRAILING_RE.test(text); }
  function stripTrailingNotifyFalse(text) { return text.replace(NOTIFY_FALSE_TRAILING_RE, ''); }

  console.log('=== Positive: notify=false detected and stripped ===');
  const input1 = 'No interruption needed.\n\nnotify=false';
  console.log('hasTrailingNotifyFalse:', hasTrailingNotifyFalse(input1));
  console.log('stripped:', JSON.stringify(stripTrailingNotifyFalse(input1)));

  console.log('\n=== Negative: plain text -- unchanged ===');
  const input2 = 'hello world';
  console.log('hasTrailingNotifyFalse:', hasTrailingNotifyFalse(input2));
  console.log('stripped:', JSON.stringify(stripTrailingNotifyFalse(input2)));

  console.log('\n=== Negative: mid-body notify=false -- no false positive ===');
  const input3 = 'notify=false is the intended behavior\nfor future replies';
  console.log('hasTrailingNotifyFalse:', hasTrailingNotifyFalse(input3));
  "
  === Positive: notify=false detected and stripped ===
  hasTrailingNotifyFalse: true
  stripped: "No interruption needed."

  === Negative: plain text -- unchanged ===
  hasTrailingNotifyFalse: false
  stripped: "hello world"

  === Negative: mid-body notify=false -- no false positive ===
  hasTrailingNotifyFalse: false
  ```

- **Observed result after fix:** trailing `notify=false` is reliably detected and stripped; plain text and mid-body `notify=false` are not falsely flagged. In the `deliverReplies` function, the stripped text is forwarded to the send layer with `disable_notification: true`, and the delivery test suite (56/56) confirms the end-to-end path: `deliverReplies` â†’ `sendMessageTelegram` receives `disable_notification: true`.

- **What was not tested:** live Telegram Bot API delivery (the `disable_notification` â†’ silent delivery wire mapping was already tested at the `sendMessageTelegram` layer).

## Scope / context

Scoped to `deliverReplies` â€” the single unified Telegram outbound reply entry point â€” covering normal replies, subagent completions, and wake/probe updates. No change to shared channel/task layer, other channel adapters, or Codex harness.

Prior PR #80737 attempted a broader fix across multiple surfaces and was voluntarily closed by the author as too wide. This PR keeps the fix narrow: one function, one convention, one channel.
